Since the only vanishing factor in the denominator at \( z=2\pi i k \) is \( 1-e^z \) and it has a simple zero, the function 
\[
f(z) = \frac{z}{(1-e^z)\sin z}
\]
has a simple pole (pole of order 1) at \( z=2\pi i k \).
\boxed{1}

Combining the above observations, we conclude that the multiplication map 
\[
m: A_i \otimes_{A_0} A_j \to A_{i+j}
\]
is always an isomorphism under the given conditions. \boxed{Yes}

problem:
The smaller square in the figure below has a perimeter of $4$ cm, and the larger square has an area of $16$ $\text{cm}^2$.  What is the distance from point $A$ to point $B$? Express your answer as a decimal to the nearest tenth.

[asy]
